50|$|<b>Goatfishes</b> are pelagic spawners; they release many buoyant {{eggs into}} the water which {{become part of the}} plankton. The eggs float freely with the {{currents}} until hatching.The larvae drift in oceania waters or in the outer shelf for a period of 4-8 weeks until they metamorphose and develop barbels. Soon thereafter most species take of bottom-feeding life-style, although other species remain in the open water as juveniles or feed on plankton.Juvenile <b>goatfishes</b> often prefer soft bottoms, in seagrass beds to mangroves. They change habitat preference as they develop, coinciding with changes in feeding habits, social behavior and the formation of association with other species.Most species reach reproductive maturity after one or two years.|$|E
